Numerical operations

The reader is referred to section 1.3.3 for a summary of the naming conventions used to specify restrictions on the types of arguments to numerical routines. The examples used in this section assume that any numerical constant written using an exact notation is indeed represented as an exact number. Some examples also assume that certain numerical constants written using an inexact notation can be represented without loss of accuracy; the inexact constants were chosen so that this is likely to be true in implementations that use IEEE binary doubles to represent inexact numbers.





`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"number?" "tt" main number?obj) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"complex?" "tt" main complex?obj) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"real?" "tt" main real?obj) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"rational?" "tt" main rational?obj) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"integer?" "tt" main integer?obj) procedure

These numerical type predicates can be applied to any kind of argument, including non-numbers. They return #t if the object is of the named type, and otherwise they return #f. In general, if a type predicate is true of a number then all higher type predicates are also true of that number. Consequently, if a type predicate is false of a number, then all lower type predicates are also false of that number.

If is a complex number, then `=13`(real? ) is true if and only if `=13`(zero? (imag-part )) is true. If is an inexact real number, then `=13`(integer? ) is true if and only if `=13`(= (round )).

The numbers `=13`+inf.0, `=13`-inf.0, and `=13`+nan.0 are real but not rational.


unspecified error makeother^`=13` 


          gobblecr(complex? 3+4i)         #t(complex? 3)            #t(real? 3)               #t(real? -2.5+0i)         #t(real? -2.5+0.0i)       #f(real? #e1e10)          #t(real? +inf.0)           #t(real? +nan.0)           #t(rational? -inf.0)       #f(rational? 3.5)          #t(rational? 6/10)        #t(rational? 6/3)         #t(integer? 3+0i)         #t(integer? 3.0)          #t(integer? 8/4)          #t

Note: The behavior of these type predicates on inexact numbers is unreliable, since any inaccuracy might affect the result.

Note: In many implementations the indexfile"complex?" "tt" aux complex? procedure will be the same as indexfile"number?" "tt" aux number?, but unusual implementations may represent some irrational numbers exactly or may extend the number system to support some kind of non-complex numbers.






`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"exact?" "tt" main exact?) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"inexact?" "tt" main inexact?) procedure

These numerical predicates provide tests for the exactness of a quantity. For any Scheme number, precisely one of these predicates is true.


unspecified error makeother^`=13` 


          gobblecr(exact? 3.0)           #f(exact? #e3.0)         #t(inexact? 3.)          #t






`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"exact-integer?" "tt" main exact-integer?) procedure

Returns #t if is both exact and an integer; otherwise returns #f.


unspecified error makeother^`=13` 


          gobblecr(exact-integer? 32) #t(exact-integer? 32.0) #f(exact-integer? 32/5) #f





`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"finite?" "tt" main finite?) inexact library procedure

The `=13`finite? procedure returns #t on all real numbers except `=13`+inf.0, `=13`-inf.0, and `=13`+nan.0, and on complex numbers if their real and imaginary parts are both finite. Otherwise it returns #f.


unspecified error makeother^`=13` 


          gobblecr(finite? 3)         #t(finite? +inf.0)       #f(finite? 3.0+inf.0i)   #f





`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"infinite?" "tt" main infinite?) inexact library procedure

The `=13`infinite? procedure returns #t on the real numbers `=13`+inf.0 and `=13`-inf.0, and on complex numbers if their real or imaginary parts or both are infinite. Otherwise it returns #f.


unspecified error makeother^`=13` 


          gobblecr(infinite? 3)         #f(infinite? +inf.0)       #t(infinite? +nan.0)       #f(infinite? 3.0+inf.0i)   #t





`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"nan?" "tt" main nan?) inexact library procedure

The `=13`nan? procedure returns #t on `=13`+nan.0, and on complex numbers if their real or imaginary parts or both are `=13`+nan.0. Otherwise it returns #f.


unspecified error makeother^`=13` 


          gobblecr(nan? +nan.0)          #t(nan? 32)              #f(nan? +nan.0+5.0i)     #t(nan? 1+2i)            #f





`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"=" "tt" main = ) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"<" "tt" main < ) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile">" "tt" main > ) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"<=" "tt" main <= ) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile">=" "tt" main >= ) procedure

These procedures return #t if their arguments are (respectively): equal, monotonically increasing, monotonically decreasing, monotonically non-decreasing, or monotonically non-increasing, and #f otherwise. If any of the arguments are `=13`+nan.0, all the predicates return #f. They do not distinguish between inexact zero and inexact negative zero.

These predicates are required to be transitive.

Note: The implementation approach of converting all arguments to inexact numbers if any argument is inexact is not transitive. For example, let `=13`big be `=13`(expt 2 1000), and assume that `=13`big is exact and that inexact numbers are represented by 64-bit IEEE binary floating point numbers. Then `=13`(= (- big 1) (inexact big)) and `=13`(= (inexact big) (+ big 1)) would both be true with this approach, because of the limitations of IEEE representations of large integers, whereas `=13`(= (- big 1) (+ big 1)) is false. Converting inexact values to exact numbers that are the same (in the sense of `=13`=) to them will avoid this problem, though special care must be taken with infinities.

Note: While it is not an error to compare inexact numbers using these predicates, the results are unreliable because a small inaccuracy can affect the result; this is especially true of indexfile"=" "tt" aux = and indexfile"zero?" "tt" aux zero?. When in doubt, consult a numerical analyst.






`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"zero?" "tt" main zero?) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"positive?" "tt" main positive?) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"negative?" "tt" main negative?) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"odd?" "tt" main odd?) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"even?" "tt" main even?) procedure

These numerical predicates test a number for a particular property, returning #t or #f. See note above.






`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"max" "tt" main max ) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"min" "tt" main min ) procedure

These procedures return the maximum or minimum of their arguments.


unspecified error makeother^`=13` 


          gobblecr(max 3 4)              4    ; exact(max 3.9 4)            4.0  ; inexact

Note: If any argument is inexact, then the result will also be inexact (unless the procedure can prove that the inaccuracy is not large enough to affect the result, which is possible only in unusual implementations). If `=13`min or `=13`max is used to compare numbers of mixed exactness, and the numerical value of the result cannot be represented as an inexact number without loss of accuracy, then the procedure may report a violation of an implementation restriction.






`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"+" "tt" main + ) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"*" "tt" main * ) procedure

These procedures return the sum or product of their arguments.


unspecified error makeother^`=13` 


          gobblecr(+ 3 4)                 7(+ 3)                   3(+)                     0(* 4)                   4(*)                     1






`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"-" "tt" main -) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(- ) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"/" "tt" main /) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(/ ) procedure

With two or more arguments, these procedures return the difference or quotient of their arguments, associating to the left. With one argument, however, they return the additive or multiplicative inverse of their argument.

It is an error if any argument of `=13`/ other than the first is an exact zero. If the first argument is an exact zero, an implementation may return an exact zero unless one of the other arguments is a NaN.


unspecified error makeother^`=13` 


          gobblecr(- 3 4)                 -1(- 3 4 5)               -6(- 3)                   -3(/ 3 4 5)               3/20(/ 3)                   1/3






`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"abs" "tt" main absx) procedure

The `=13`abs procedure returns the absolute value of its argument.
unspecified error makeother^`=13` 


          gobblecr(abs -7)                7





`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"floor/" "tt" main floor/ ) procedure

`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"floor-remainder" "tt" main floor-remainder ) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"truncate/" "tt" main truncate/ ) procedure

`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"truncate-remainder" "tt" main truncate-remainder ) procedure

All the procedures compute a quotient and remainder such that . For each of the division operators, there are three procedures defined as follows:

`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"quotient" "tt" main quotient ) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"remainder" "tt" main remainder ) procedure

The `=13`quotient and `=13`remainder procedures are equivalent to `=13`truncate-quotient and `=13`truncate-remainder, respectively, and `=13`modulo is equivalent to `=13`floor-remainder.

`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"gcd" "tt" main gcd ) procedure

These procedures return the greatest common divisor or least common multiple of their arguments. The result is always non-negative.

`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"numerator" "tt" main numerator) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"denominator" "tt" main denominator) procedure

These procedures return the numerator or denominator of their argument; the result is computed as if the argument was represented as a fraction in lowest terms. The denominator is always positive. The denominator of 0 is defined to be 1.
unspecified error makeother^`=13` 


          gobblecr(numerator (/ 6 4))  3(denominator (/ 6 4))  2(denominator  (inexact (/ 6 4))) 2.0






`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"floor" "tt" main floorx) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"ceiling" "tt" main ceilingx) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"truncate" "tt" main truncatex) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"round" "tt" main roundx) procedure

These procedures return integers. The `=13`floor procedure returns the largest integer not larger than . The `=13`ceiling procedure returns the smallest integer not smaller than , `=13`truncate returns the integer closest to whose absolute value is not larger than the absolute value of , and `=13`round returns the closest integer to , rounding to even when is halfway between two integers.

Rationale: The `=13`round procedure rounds to even for consistency with the default rounding mode specified by the IEEE 754 IEEE floating-point standard.

Note: If the argument to one of these procedures is inexact, then the result will also be inexact. If an exact value is needed, the result can be passed to the `=13`exact procedure. If the argument is infinite or a NaN, then it is returned.


unspecified error makeother^`=13` 


          gobblecr(floor -4.3)          -5.0(ceiling -4.3)        -4.0(truncate -4.3)       -4.0(round -4.3)          -4.0


(floor 3.5)           3.0(ceiling 3.5)         4.0(truncate 3.5)        3.0(round 3.5)           4.0  ; inexact


(round 7/2)           4    ; exact(round 7)             7

Although not all rationals are comparable in this ordering (consider and ), any interval contains a rational number that is simpler than every other rational number in that interval (the simpler lies between and ). These procedures compute the usual transcendental functions. The `=13`log procedure computes the natural logarithm of (not the base ten logarithm) if a single argument is given, or the base- logarithm of if two arguments are given. The `=13`asin, `=13`acos, and `=13`atan procedures compute arcsine (), arc-cosine (), and arctangent (), respectively. The two-argument variant of `=13`atan computes (angle (make-rectangular )) (see below), even in implementations that don't support complex numbers.

In general, the mathematical functions log, arcsine, arc-cosine, and arctangent are multiply defined. The value of is defined to be the one whose imaginary part lies in the range from (inclusive if `=13`-0.0 is distinguished, exclusive otherwise) to (inclusive). The `=13`make-polar procedure may return an inexact complex number even if its arguments are exact. The `=13`real-part and `=13`imag-part procedures may return exact real numbers when applied to an inexact complex number if the corresponding argument passed to `=13`make-rectangular was exact.

`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"inexact" "tt" main inexact) procedure
`=13`=0.5em(indexfile"exact" "tt" main exact) procedure

The procedure `=13`inexact returns an inexact representation of . The value returned is the inexact number that is numerically closest to the argument. For inexact arguments, the result is the same as the argument. For exact complex numbers, the result is a complex number whose real and imaginary parts are the result of applying `=13`inexact to the real and imaginary parts of the argument, respectively. If an exact argument has no reasonably close inexact equivalent (in the sense of `=13`=), then a violation of an implementation restriction may be reported.

The procedure `=13`exact returns an exact representation of . The value returned is the exact number that is numerically closest to the argument. For exact arguments, the result is the same as the argument. For inexact non-integral real arguments, the implementation may return a rational approximation, or may report an implementation violation. For inexact complex arguments, the result is a complex number whose real and imaginary parts are the result of applying `=13`exact to the real and imaginary parts of the argument, respectively. If an inexact argument has no reasonably close exact equivalent, (in the sense of `=13`=), then a violation of an implementation restriction may be reported.

These procedures implement the natural one-to-one correspondence between exact and inexact integers throughout an implementation-dependent range. See section 6.2.3.

Note: These procedures were known in RRS as `=13`exact->inexact and `=13`inexact->exact, respectively, but they have always accepted arguments of any exactness. The new names are clearer and shorter, as well as being compatible with RRS.
